[
    {
        "content": "<p>Why is it that the category of copresheaves of some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is sometimes given as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[\\mathcal{C},\\mathrm{Set}]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> and other times as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[\\mathcal{C},\\mathrm{Set}]^\\mathrm{op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 467715611,
        "sender_full_name": "Keith Elliott Peterson",
        "timestamp": 1725510566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Where is it given as the latter? I've only ever seen the former</p>",
        "id": 467720710,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1725513123
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The appropriate definition is typically the latter, because it has a universal property with respect to C: it is the free completion under small limits.</p>",
        "id": 467723549,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1725514294
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As to why some people use a different convention, I imagine many people aren't aware of the reason to use the latter convention, and the former seems more intuitive.</p>",
        "id": 467724264,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1725514611
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Interesting.  I would refer to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[C,\\rm Set]^{\\rm op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> as the \"co-presheaf category\" of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> for the reasons given by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276092\">@Nathanael Arkor</span> .  But in my head this is bracketed as \"co-(presheaf category)\", and I would not call its objects \"copresheaves\" or refer to it as the \"category of copresheaves\" -- to me, those would refer to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[C,\\rm Set]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 467762765,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1725525150
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the latter is also the natural counterpoint of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> Psh(C) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> for Isbell duality, precisely because you have the co-yoneda embedding <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> C \\to [C, \\mathrm{Set}]^{\\mathrm{op}} </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 467786073,
        "sender_full_name": "Josselin Poiret",
        "timestamp": 1725529347
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Using \"copresheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>\" to mean <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[C,\\mathrm{Set}]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> can be justified by the convention that the \"co-\" prefix  refers to what we get by applying a given construction to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^{\\mathrm{op}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 467815614,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1725534280
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would also tend to use \"copresheaf category\" rather than \"category of copresheaves\", but I do think it would be confusing to use both these terms in a single paper, but with different meanings.</p>",
        "id": 467819927,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1725534839
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I agree.  But in separate papers it could be okay.</p>",
        "id": 467887115,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1725547979
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually I don't really like the word \"copresheaf\" at all -- I prefer \"Set-valued functor\".  It annoys me sufficiently already that we have to have a separate word for \"contravariant Set-valued functor\" and that that word is derogated by a prefix like \"pre-\"; why do we then have to double-dualize to talk about <em>covariant</em> functors?  (-:O</p>",
        "id": 467887664,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1725548075
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the enriched context, presheaves and copresheaves are not necessarily functors, so I do think it is useful to have separate terms. (Though whether \"presheaf\" and \"copresheaf\" are good terms is a different question...)</p>",
        "id": 467888387,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1725548210
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe one could use \"left-distributor\" and \"right-distributor\" in analogy with \"left-module\" and \"right-module\" <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span></p>",
        "id": 467889052,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1725548340
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or one could just say \"left module\" and \"right module\".  (But then one has to remember which is \"left\" and which is \"right\"...)</p>",
        "id": 467889376,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1725548401
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's true, but I personally do find it helpful to have a specific term for modules of categories.</p>",
        "id": 467889645,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1725548449
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But maybe that's simply a habit to be broken.</p>",
        "id": 467889810,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1725548480
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>covariant vs. contravariant rather than left vs. right?</p>",
        "id": 467902678,
        "sender_full_name": "Josselin Poiret",
        "timestamp": 1725551200
    }
]